# Integer Overflow

Overflow occurs when a value becomes greater than the maximum value that a data type can store.

Example

```java
byte x = 127;

x++;

System.out.println(x);
```

Output

```
-128
```

Reason

A `byte` stores values only from:

```
-128

↓

127
```

After reaching 127, the next value wraps around to -128.

---

# Underflow

Underflow occurs when a value becomes smaller than the minimum value that a data type can store.

Example

```java
byte x = -128;

x--;

System.out.println(x);
```

Output

```
127
```

The value wraps around to the maximum value.

---

# Precision Loss

Precision Loss occurs when a higher-precision data type is converted into a lower-precision data type.

Example

```java
double d = 123.987654;

float f = (float)d;

System.out.println(f);
```

The output may not preserve all decimal digits because `float` has lower precision than `double`.

